'2022-03-22T17:08:33Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'NONE', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': "
In the documentation, it says that intents should not include the following characters: `:` `$` `&`

However in the LUIS portal, you get a different set of restrictions:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5193014/158861587-da4f358c-9baa-4739-bca1-ceff2cc0c98c.png)

And if you create intents using the Authoring API, it's possible to use some of the characters that the portal does not allow, for example I am able to create an intent called `What day is it?` via the API, but not in the portal. If I then try to rename it in the portal I see the validation error:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/5193014/158861997-787b2160-40f7-4c2f-810e-7b1d74f78784.png)

Can it be made clear in the docs what characters are allowed, and can it be enforced consistently in the portal and the API?

'2022-03-07T18:07:35Z', 'closed_at': None, 'author_association': 'CONTRIBUTOR', 'active_lock_reason': None, 'body': 'The docs page suggests to hardcode these variables:
```csharp
var key = "PASTE_YOUR_LUIS_AUTHORING_SUBSCRIPTION_KEY_HERE";

var authoringEndpoint = "PASTE_YOUR_LUIS_AUTHORING_ENDPOINT_HERE";
var predictionEndpoint = "PASTE_YOUR_LUIS_PREDICTION_ENDPOINT_HERE";
```
and
```csharp
var appName = "Contoso Pizza Company";
var versionId = "0.1";
var intentName = "OrderPizzaIntent";
```

Shouldn't all of these variables come from configuration instead of hardcoding?

I understand that for the sake of simplicity, hardcoding is easier for tutorials, but I'm more worried about the `key` variable.
Is this key variable supposed to kept secret? The luis.ai interface and this code sample gives me the impression that you don't have to worry about keeping the key secret.

If it should be kept secret, I think there should at least be a warning or advice to keep it secret on this page.
Or maybe use .NET user-secrets or link readers to how to use user-secrets for local development.

my colleagues) multiple days to find out that my user needs Owner or Contributor role on the language resource. It is documented in the article but it is too easily missed.

I suggest to use
(1) an explicit section that describes the required roles for the users using the service and
(2) another section that describes the roles required for the language resource's managed identity.
(3) Besides, it would be good to know how the storage account can be accessed without managed identity (in case it's supported).

Please be also more clear about the roles required for the managed identity (is it an AND or an OR of the mentioned roles) as well as the support of Azure Data Lake Gen 2 (see my other feedback for that article).
